Universe](/wiki/Miss_Universe "Miss Universe") pageant since the [pageant's
first edition in 1952](/wiki/Miss_Universe_1952 "Miss Universe 1952").

## Table of Miss Universe runners-up and
finalists[[edit](/w/index.php?title=List_of_Miss_Universe_runners-
up_and_finalists&action=edit&section=1 "Edit section: Table of Miss Universe
runners-up and finalists")]

The pageant has awarded a top-five finalists from 1952 to 1989 and from 2001
up to 2014, with the first, second, third and fourth runner-up being awarded.
From 1990 to 1997, the number of finalists was increased to six. From 1998 to
2000 and since 2015, it was reverted to five but only up to the second runner-
up was awarded (regardless if the pageant post-announces the placements of the
other 2 delegates who made it to the Top 5).

This table shows the top-five finalists of each competition, from its
inception in [1952](/wiki/Miss_Universe_1952 "Miss Universe 1952").

### 1st runner-up[[edit](/w/index.php?title=List_of_Miss_Universe_runners-
up_and_finalists&action=edit&section=3 "Edit section: 1st runner-up")]

The first runner-up of each edition of Miss Universe is the second placer
behind the candidate who is crowned as Miss Universe. In some cases, she shall
take over the title of Miss Universe, if:

  * The outgoing titleholder cannot fulfill her duties. This could happen and may result to resignation, giving up the title, or dethronement
  * The titleholder is dethroned due to deeds that violate the organization's policies.

This has only happened in [2002](/wiki/Miss_Universe_2002 "Miss Universe
2002").

There were instances that the winner is not replaced by the first runner-up,
when she decides to voluntarily resign from her position, given the formal
permission from the organization (1952 and 1974).

This table lists the number of 1st runner-up titles by country. There are some
special considerations:

  * [Hawaii](/wiki/Hawaii "Hawaii") competed as an independent territory from 1952 to 1959, before it joined the United States, holding one 1st runner-up title on its own.
  * The [United Kingdom](/wiki/United_Kingdom "United Kingdom") (currently competing under the name of _Great Britain_) competed separatedly as England (from 1955 to 1962 and then again from 1964 to 1990), Scotland (from 1961 to 1986 and then again from 1988 to 1990) and Wales (from 1961 to 1990), holding a total of four 1st runner-up titles which are counted together.
  * As [Panama](/wiki/Panama "Panama") took over the Miss Universe title in [2002](/wiki/Miss_Universe_2002 "Miss Universe 2002"), it is unknown if the 1st runner-up position was taken by another candidate after the succession took place.

### 2nd runner-up[[edit](/w/index.php?title=List_of_Miss_Universe_runners-
up_and_finalists&action=edit&section=4 "Edit section: 2nd runner-up")]

The second runner-up of each edition of Miss Universe is the third placer
behind the candidate who is crowned as Miss Universe and the first runner-up
(second placer). Although it has never happened, the second runner-up is
supposed to take over the Miss Universe title if both the original winner and
the first runner-up are unable to fulfill their duties/resign their titles.
For example, if a Miss Universe winner is required to give up her title and
the first runner-up is unable/does not want to assume the winner's position,
the title then passes to the second runner-up.

This table lists the number of 2nd runner-up titles by country. There are some
special considerations as well:

  * [Hawaii](/wiki/Hawaii "Hawaii") competed as an independent territory from 1952 to 1959, before it joined the United States, holding one 2nd runner-up title on its own.
  * The [United Kingdom](/wiki/United_Kingdom "United Kingdom") (currently competing under the name of _Great Britain_) competed separatedly as England (from 1955 to 1962 and then again from 1964 to 1990), Scotland (from 1961 to 1986 and then again from 1988 to 1990) and Wales (from 1961 to 1990), holding a total of five 2nd runner-up titles which are counted together.
  * It is unknown if Zhuo Ling, [Miss Universe 2002](/wiki/Miss_Universe_2002 "Miss Universe 2002") second runner-up, took over the first runner-up position after Justine Pasek took over the winner's place, as no official statements regarding this matter were made by the organization.
